    "John Trapp": "Unleavened cake of fine flour mingled with oil. ] Sincerity is the mother of serenity; truth, of tranquillity.\nVer.\n4. In their seasons, ] i.e., Once a year.\nVer.\n4. In their seasons, ] i.e., Once a year. [v_Exo_12_18]\nVer.",
    "Lloyd R. Bailey": ") and the \u201choly convocations\u201d; furthermore, it is not\nincluded in the summary of the section at vv. 37-38; (2) the\n\u201cappointed feasts\u201d (vv. 4-38), with a formal introduction (\nv. 4) and\nconclusion (vv. 37-38); and (3) an appendix concerning the last of\nthe appointed feasts (vv. 39-43) that also provides an appropriate and\ntraditional reminder of the overall Mosaic (Sinaitic) context of the\ncovenant: \u201cI am the LORD your God.\u201d\nThe Sabbath `[object_Sabbath_Ref]` regulation was perhaps added by H as an appropriate\nintroduction to the whole, since the concept of \u201crest\u201d (related to the\nword \u201cSabbath `[object_Sabbath_Ref]`\u201d) occurs throughout the chapter. Appropriately, then,\nthere are seven great annual observances.\nThe seven annual convocations may be divided into those that\noccur in the spring (vv. 5-22) and those that occur in the fall (vv. 23-\n43), with heavy emphasis upon what happens in the first month of\neach section of these two divisions of the year. The description of\neach seasonal celebration ends with H\u2019s traditional authoritative\nrefrain, \u201cI am the LORD your God.\u201d\nAncient Israel, like other societies in the area, based its economy\nupon agriculture and herding and thus arranged its calendar accord-\ningly. The fundamental and conspicuous events, therefore, will be\n\u201charvest festivals\u201d: the spring lambing season (\u201cPassover\u201d), grain\nharvests (e.g., \u201cWeeks\u201d), and the ripening of grapes (\u201cBooths `[plant_Booths_Lev_23]`\u201d).\nOther observances have later been inserted into this annual agricul-\ntural sequence.\nIn outlining its new calendar, H introduces several innovations\nand emphases:\n(1) Rather than let nature dictate the dates of harvest (e.g., with\nvariations that will be caused by fluctuations in the\nweather), H has assigned a specific date to each cel-\nebration and has carefully outlined the rituals\nthat are to be performed.2 This is in keeping\nwith an emphasis of the priests\u2019 manual\n(the P Code) that rituals must be done at\nthe right (and specific) time, at the speci-\nfied place, and in the right manner.\nDivinely ordained order thus overcomes\nthe forces of chaos and uncertainty. (See\nthe section on \u201cLeviticus as Theology\u201d in\nthe Introduction.)\n(2) H began the practice of referring to\nmonths by numerical order rather than\nby the older system of month-names (e.g.,\n4. At 14:26-38, a repetition and intensification of the divine judgment that had been given\nat 14:20-25), now recognizable as \u201cP\u201d by the inclusion of Aaron `[char_Aaron_Exo_6]` (not mentioned in",
    "Andrew Bonar, Andrew E. Hill": "ver. 4, where Uzziel's sons, who\nwere only Levites, went to them), not at the golden altar.\nVer. 4-\n4. There is no hint in the New Testament that\nthey have been repealed; but, on the contrary, Paul `[char_Paul_Act_13]`'s\nhorror, expressed in 1 Cor.\n4. It was renewed, weekly. Thus it never\nmoulded. It was fresh at all times. For so is the\nAntitype, ever fresh to us, as truly as in apostolic days.\nHe never waxes old; this food never moulds. You may\nget the same joy in believing on him, the same peace, the\nsame assurance, that were found in apostolic days; and\nmay be moved with the same love and zeal and holiness,\nby feeding on the same primitive food.\nver. 4), no reap-\ning even of what grew of itself; they might pluck the\nfew grapes that grew on \"the undressed vine (\nver. 4, 5); but it did so with great enlargement. It\nexhibits some of the joy, and the causes of the joy, of that\nmillennial time ("
